snippet.textDisplay:
This game was interesting. First half went kind of like I expected it would. The Saints were finding unique ways to beat the Vikings defense. Kamara wasn’t any more effective than he’d been all regular season, but the versatility and effort of Taysom Hill was enough to catch the Vikings in the wrong positions and gain some ground for the Saints. However, Brees threw a costly interception at the end of the first half, and the Vikings went right down the field to steal a touchdown that turned out to be game changing. Then in the second half, Brees made another costly error by fumbling the ball as he was being sacked. Will Lutz even missed a field goal at one point, which he hardly did all season. Talk about costly errors. They could only tie the game with the time they had left, and that was the last time the Saints offense would see the field for the season.



I know people are all excited about Kirk Cousins finally delivering in a high-pressure situation. Give him credit, he made a great throw to Thielen and another well placed ball to Kyle Rudolph in overtime to win the game. However, he was not playing well in regulation. Diggs didn’t get a reception until the second half, some of his throws and decisions weren’t that great. That being said he was good enough for this one. Dalvin Cook faced a great front 7 and wasn’t able to beat them all by himself.



Overall the Vikings defense was the best unit in the game. Give the Vikings a lot of credit for playing that well in a harsh environment against a 13-3 team. However, I think a lot of this game came down to the mistakes made by the Saints offense. Where was this record-breaking Michael Thomas in the second half? With your season on the line, if Drew Brees can’t find him maybe you have to start thinking about a future with a new quarterback.



It's really fascinating there’s been a league-wide epiphany that running the football is essential to a good football team. Without tandem partner Mark Ingram, Alvin Kamara struggled throughout the season, even with a decent offensive line. The Vikings got a healthy Dalvin Cook for a full season and he carried their offense to a winning season.

snippet.textDisplay: The 49ers need to be careful, very careful now. Remember back in 1987 when Minnesota backed into the playoffs as a wild card team??? First stop was New Orleans in the wild card game in which Minnesota blew the Saints out in their first ever playoff game.  Next week the Vikings played the top seeded 49ers in S.F in the Divisional Round . against Montana, Rice, Clark, Craig, Lott, etc.. The 49ers were a 12 point favorite in the game. The Vikings routed the 49ers in which Rice had two catches for 20 yards, Montana was taken out of the game in third quarter. after 12 for 24 96 yards no TD's , Dwight Clark had one catch for 13 yards in his final game as a pro. Vikings wide receiver Anthony Carter had 10 catches for 227 yards against the 49ers. The Vikings lost the next week in NFC Championship Game to the Redskins in D.C. during the final minute of the game.

snippet.textDisplay:
I was pretty worried toward the end of the game. I thought the Vikings were gonna throw the game away, choke under pressure, whatever. Full of surprises, this game was. Good and bad. Very glad the Vikings won this one. Hopefully they make it to the superbowl, but honestly my expectations are low.

Now, if the Saints used Hill the whole time instead of Brees, they likely would have won that game. He is one hell of a player. I say player instead of quarterback because he can run, he can catch, and he can block. Hell, this guy is built like a linebacker. He can just plow through people. I only wish he played for the Vikings instead. I'm still skeptical about Cousins. I don't think he's a superbowl caliber QB, but he has improved since last season. We'll see what happens.
